    <table border=0 cellpadding=3 cellspacing=0 bgcolor=cfcfbb width=100%><tr><td align=left>
    <font size=3 color="#363636"><b>Zen and the Art of Loot Creation</b></font><br>
    <font size=2>
    Posted on Sunday, April 01 @ 17:16:29 EDT by <a href="http://www.noows.com">zamtil</a><font size=2>Contributed by: <a href="user.php?op=userinfo&uname=Millie">Millie</a></font></td></tr></table></td></tr></table><br><a href="search.php?query=&topic=30"><img src=images/topics/everquest.gif border=0 Alt="EverQuest" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10></a>Dear Infinitely Wise and Benevolent Verant Developers,
<br><br>
Last night my guildmates and I assembled in the Temple of Veeshan for what was to be a fun-filled attempt at Gozzrem, one of the Temple's resident dragons. Gozzy fell, and we were introduced once more to the horror better known as "Itemization: Verant Style."
<br><br>
I'm still not sure whether it was shock, hilarity or outright terror that got the best of us when the loot table was rattled off in guild chat. Whatever the case, I was laughing to the point of tears. Among the spoils of the Gozzrem fight were a held item with 5 ac and Necklace of Superiority stats (anemic at best), and of all things a 2hb, 35/50, -106 hp (yes, minus) "Shovel of the Harvest" -- a ridiculous item which I interpret to be a tongue-in-cheek gag aimed at would-be "farmers" of the zone. 
<br><br>
<br><br><br><br>The encounter with Gozzrem was very difficult, and simply getting to her requires a fair deal of ingenuity and a lion's share of hassle. Is this the sort of loot we are to expect as the reward commensurate with Gozzrem's risk? Somehow I suspect not. Rather, I'd like to believe Verant has simply messed up once again in assessing the risk-vs-reward ratio of one of its entirely untested zones.
<br><br>
The exact same phenomenon occurred when we first hit Veeshan's Peak back in Kunark. You remember that place, right? And of course you must recall the controversy that emerged when we found loot off incredibly hard dragons that was of slightly lesser quality than the stuff we could farm in Sebilis. Well imagine this: many months later, in a top-of-the-line zone in Velious, we are finding loot that's of MUCH lesser quality than what we could find in Sebilis.
<br><br>
Please, Verant. All we ask is that you at the very least -try- to itemize your zones correctly. You give us precious little incentive to explore uncharted zones when we know it will be months of haggling and whining before any of the outright crap we uncover will be turned into something slightly less offensive to the inventory. 
<br><br>
I have no doubt that ToV loot will eventually be upgraded. But why bother with all this 'live tuning' in the first place? Why not simply think in advance, for a change, about the difficulty of a zone, and consequently, the richness of its rewards. It is my understanding that different designers create and itemize the various zones, and that they work independently of one another. Here's an idea -- try having these people coordinate their efforts. This crazy, newfangled concept simply means that Beavis, working on a level 60+ dungeon, knows to put better loot in his zone than Butthead, who's designing a level 35 - 45 area. 
<br><br>
Risk versus Reward: It's not a revolutionary concept. You fail miserably each time you open a new zone. And yet, at least on paper, there seems to be no reason why you should.
<br><br>
Perhaps the next time you hire Marion Berry to design and itemize your high-level encounters, you should make sure he's ON the wagon.</td></tr></table><br></td><td>&nbsp;</td><td valign=top width=200>
